	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The glass is 4:3 (Or at least, has been since ... uh, late 1960s?)<br /><br />Old glass CRTs didn't have a fixed number of pixels. By changing the specific rate at which a digital device emits pixels, the width of each pixel changes accordingly.<br /><br />So the specific amount of image that's encoded in the signal (e.g. 640x480i that's overscanned so only â‰ˆ600x448 is visible) means that a 256x192 console with square pixels would be &quot;windowboxed&quot; like the C64.<br /><br />Consoles like the Master System that drew 192-scanline-high video modes instead often stretched the pixels a little bit horizontally to make the display more nearly full-width; correspondingly the screen is letterboxed.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


